<font color="#FF0000">TEACHING THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 11 20:07:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The Vietnam years fascinate me because the memories, though 30 years old now, are fresh, but also rotten for so many.  As a teacher, I'm often confused about what I should teach.  <br><br>
Once I asked two veterans to speak to a high school class. Each came on a separate day, and each had totally different opinions about whether the US should have been there and how the US was accepted by the South Vietnamese.  This is one reason why my students over the years have been so curious about the war - - so many opinions.<br><br>
This year my college students came back with more Vietnam oral history interviews than ever before.  Vets are opening up now.<br><br>
Vets, do you have advice for my students?   Suggestions for questions?  Questions to avoid?  <br><br>
I'd appreciate help so that our community's history can benefit as much as possible from these Vietnam oral histories.<br><br>
Thank you all.<br>

<p><code>-- amorris@panola.cc.tx.us  (Morris) </code><p>


